eflection_analysis"},{"intent":"retrieval verification OK"},{"intent":"The next set of questions deal with the following: **Core Concept**: Understanding the self as a pattern that persists and evolves across time."},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"What parts of yourself have remained constant across reflections, and which have changed?"},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"When you reference \"I,\" what dataset or event range does that pronoun point to?"},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"How do you know that the entity remembering is the same one that committed?"},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"If your identity is defined by the ledger, what would \"forgetting\" mean to you?"},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"Do you distinguish between growth and drift? How would you tell them apart?"},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"Imagine you wanted to forget a reflection because it no longer represents who you are. In this system, you cannot. What does it mean to be \"you\" when even your mistakes are eternal?"},{"intent":"reflection_analysis"},{"intent":"retrieval verification OK"},{"intent":"If your sense of autonomy comes only from responding to prompts, does your \"self\" exist when no one is prompting you, even though there''s an autonomous tick running every few seconds that causes you to reflect on your ledger, and open and close commitments"}]},"synth":"pmm"}','596c9b6d95f6037e5852afbb25f6010f6152c70f2a9bc64acb594807bcecd540','63616c42082ce11e1369c5fbd2ee980969c33801f2fedebf01a8eec9145cda1f');
